Inflation in Europe leapt because of food
The increasing inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
The November price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after 2.6 per cent in October the annual inflation rate was 3.1 per cent, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union announced.
The official forecast predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the basic interest rate by reducing, together with rising commodity prices and declining unemployment, the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "do away" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about this later on.
In Germany, November inflation represents 3.3 percent of the 15-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The euro area inflation has shrivel up due to rapidly rising food and energy prices.
The term prices of wheat have risen by 88 percent, and soybeans have also reached the highest levels since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets increased by 52 percent this year, and last month it already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but it will decline to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain at approximately 3% over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to immediately reduce interest rates twice in 2008.
