Depleted Memory
After more than sixty years in the confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which correspond to the fates of the 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are opened to the public.
47 million archival documents stored 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were available until now only for "humanities" purposes, which means individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorised persons.
Eleven States entrusted with the management of archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Given that the ratification process for this agreement by all States is over, opening yesterday has become effective.
Sensitivity
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow us to examine "especially the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-rouge, CICR).
Until recently, several states, among them Germany, have been opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
What are the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or arresters built by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced work subjected to civilian citizenship, providing them with evidence of their internalisation in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is only a limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for Anti-Semitism Studies of Berlin Technische Universität in 2006.
