Congress approved MiFID transposition effective from 1 November
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the vote of the Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate in the draft law, the Government has subjected the hearing of the regulation developing the new law to the effect that both of them enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of each party have consistently highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities needed for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the European Union supervisory authorities.
This new regulation will allow the provision of financial advice services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial service companies (ESIS), financial advice companies (AIFs), which join securities companies, securities brokering offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of financial instruments is being expanded so that multilateral trading systems and internalisation systems are connected to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stock brokers.
The law further obliges investment service providers to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and risk management and requires a report of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the deliberations of the Congress's Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which it is noted that the securitised claims are considered to be a "complicated" financial instrument in view of the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the USA with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the Directive was used for the legal definition of functions which codifiers may hold in the field of economics and management 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of a Royal Decree setting out the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading services and customer acquisitions for various investment firms at the same time.
